column69: Assemblage A, Rockhampton Group, east-central Queensland
column82: Numerous outcrops in Lion Creek block, Ridgeland block, and Fitzroy block, W of Rockhampton, near Fitzroy River, east-central Queensland.
column123: Age calls based on corals, brachiopods, conodonts. Zones are brachiopod zones of Roberts (1975). A: Spirifer sol to Schellwienella burlingtonensis; B: Orthotetes australis to Delepinia aspinosa; C: D. aspinosa to Rhipidomella fortimuscula; D: Marginirugus barringtonensis. A is late Tournaisian; B-D are early to late Visean.
column124: Most limestones are oolitic grainstones. These are within some 2000m of marine siltstone and sandstone. Some of these are allochthonous, but the discussion of geologic context makes it clear that the limestones largely represent intervals of carbonate deposition within the longer siliciclastic sequence.
column138: Overall carbonate sequence is shallow water, representing W-E transect with following biofacies: 1. forebank slope; 2. biohermal ooid bank 3. ooid bank/shallow water mobile sands; 4. biostromal open shallow shelf; 5. shallow water mobile sands (open shelf); 6. offshore silt (open shelf); 7. nearshore mobile sands. Assemblage A includes biofacies 3&4; B has 1-3; C has 2-4; D has 2,3,5-7.
column166: Paper is on corals. Other elements sometimes mentioned in passing.

column123: Age calls based on corals, brachiopods, conodonts. Zones are brachiopod zones of Roberts (1975). A: Spirifer sol to Schellwienella burlingtonensis; B: Orthotetes australis to Delepinia aspinosa; C: D. aspinosa to Rhipidomella fortimuscula; D: Marginirugus barringtonensis. A is late Tournaisian; B-D are early to late Visean.
column124: Most limestones are oolitic grainstones. These are within some 2000m of marine siltstone and sandstone. Some of these are allochthonous, but the discussion of geologic context makes it clear that the limestones largely represent intervals of carbonate deposition within the longer siliciclastic sequence.
column138: Overall carbonate sequence is shallow water, representing W-E transect with following biofacies: 1. forebank slope; 2. biohermal ooid bank 3. ooid bank/shallow water mobile sands; 4. biostromal open shallow shelf; 5. shallow water mobile sands (open shelf); 6. offshore silt (open shelf); 7. nearshore mobile sands. Assemblage A includes biofacies 3&4; B has 1-3; C has 2-4; D has 2,3,5-7.
column166: Paper is on corals. Other elements sometimes mentioned in passing.

column82: Lweinsbrook is situated 2.5 miles south-east of the town of Gresford [Lat and Long provided are for Gresford] and approximately 40 miles north-east of Newcastle (text-fig. 1).    Locality grid reference number 46089882 from Dungog 1 Mile Military Sheet
column123: the age is described as Upper Tournaisian

column124: bed

column69: NUL 811, Cobark Creek Section, Berrico Creek FM, New South Wales, Australia
column82: On bank of Cobark River
column83: 5.5 km northeast of Rawdon Vale village
column84: N.S.W. Grid reference 750-487 Cobark 1:31680 Sheet    Lat and Long estimates are for the village of Cobark. N.S.W.
column126: granualr, coarse grained, lithic sandstone. In thin section, the sandstones have phenoclasts composed chiefly of subangular to subrounded clear quartz and altered plagioclase, biotite, muscovite, calcite and lithic fragments (mainly volcanic rocks). Rounded to well rounded calcitit oolites nucleated on some of these phenoclasts are also present. The sandstones are cemented by calcite, iron-oxide and mica minerals and also have a fine matrix. They accumulated close to the shoreline under relatively high energy conditions.
column167: All type and illustrated specimens (Rawdonia nasharae gen. et sp. nov.) are housed in the Department of Geology, University of Newcastle, N.S.W.

column126: granualr, coarse grained, lithic sandstone. In thin section, the sandstones have phenoclasts composed chiefly of subangular to subrounded clear quartz and altered plagioclase, biotite, muscovite, calcite and lithic fragments (mainly volcanic rocks). Rounded to well rounded calcitit oolites nucleated on some of these phenoclasts are also present. The sandstones are cemented by calcite, iron-oxide and mica minerals and also have a fine matrix. They accumulated close to the shoreline under relatively high energy conditions.

column82: Lat & long coordinates for the town of Hilldale, NSW. "L.53 Greenhills is situated within a 200 yard radius of 46609790 Paterson One Mile Military Sheet, approximately 1.5 miles south-west of the village of Hilldale on the North Coast Railway Line 10 miles south of Dungog."
column123: Age: "Middle Visean (Cu III-alpha)". The particular group or formation that this locality belongs us unclear. The regional stratigraphic relationships are obscured by laterally rapid facies changes and structural complexity.
column124: There is no written description of the L.53 lithologies in Roberts (1964), only a generalized strat section (fig. 2). L.53 consists of two fossiliferous horizons seperated by a vertical distance of approximately 5 feet. The lower horizon is in a unit of "darkgrey fossiliferous siltsonte", the upper horizone is in "coarse fossiliferous sandstone".
column165: specimens reposited at the University of New South Wales.
